nd]]'' (Riverside, 1960)\n*''[[Starting Time]]'' (Jazzland, 1961)\n*''[[Bearcat (album)|Bearcat]]'' (Jazzland, 1962)\n*''[[These are My Roots: Clifford Jordan Plays Leadbelly]]'' (Atlantic, 1965)\n*''[[Glass Bead Games]]'' (Strata-East, 1974)\n*''[[Half Note]]'' (SteepleChase, 1974 [1985])\n*''[[Night of the Mark VII]]'' (Muse, 1975)\n*''[[On Stage Vol. 1]]'' (SteepleChase, 1975 [1977])\n*''[[On Stage Vol. 2]]'' (SteepleChase, 1975 [1978])\n*''[[On Stage Vol. 3]]'' (SteepleChase, 1975 [1979])\n*''[[Firm Roots (Clifford Jordan album)|Firm Roots]]'' (Steeplechase, 1975)\n*''[[The Highest Mountain]]'' (Steeplechase, 1975)\n\n'''With [[Eric Kloss]]'''\n*''[[First Class Kloss!]]'' (Prestige, 1967)\n\n'''With [[Abbey Lincoln]]'''\n*''[[Abbey Is Blue]]'' (Riverside, 1959)\n\n'''With [[Pat Martino]]'''\n*''[[Strings!]]'' (Prestige, 1967)\n\n'''With [[Christian McBride]]'''\n*''[[New York Time (Christian McBride album)|New York Time]]'' (Chesky, 2006)\n\n'''With [[Charles McPherson (musician)|Charles McPherson]]'''\n*''[[From This Moment On!]]'' (Prestige, 1968)\n*''[[Horizons (Charles McPherson album)|Horizons]]'' (Prestige, 1968)\n\n'''With [[Blue Mitchell]]'''\n*''[[The Cup Bearers]]'' (Riverside, 1962)\n*''[[Boss Horn]]'' (1966)\n*''[[Stratosonic Nuances]]'' (RCA, 1975)\n*''[[Summer Soft]]'' (Impulse!, 1977)\n\n'''With [[Frank Morgan (musician)|Frank Morgan]]'''\n*''[[Easy Living (Frank Morgan album)|Easy Living]]'' (Contemporary, 1985)\n*''[[Lament (Frank Morgan album)|Lament]]'' (Contemporary, 1986)\n*''[[Bebop Lives!]]'' (Contemporary, 1987)\n*''[[Love, Lost & Found]]'' (Telarc, 1995)\n\n'''With [[Lee Morgan]]'''\n*''[[Caramba! (Lee Morgan album)|Caramba!]]'' (Blue Note, 1968)\n*''[[The Sixth Sense (Lee Morgan album)|The Sixth Sense]]'' (Blue Note, 1968)\n'''With [[David \"Fathead\" Newman]]'''\n*''[[Resurgence!]]'' (Muse, 1981)\n*''[[Davey Blue]]'' (HighNote, 2002)\n*''[[Diamondhead (David \"Fathead\" Newman album)|Diamondhead]]'' (HighNote, 1988)\n'''With [[Houston Person]]'''\n*''[[Chocomotive]]'' (Prestige, 1967)\n*''[[Trust in Me (album)|Trust in Me]]'' (Prestige, 1967)\n*''[[Blue Odyssey]]'' (Prestige, 1968)\n*''[[Broken Windows, Empty Hallways]]'' (Prestige, 1972)\n*''[[The Big Horn]]'' (Muse, 1976 [1979])\n*''[[Very Personal|Very PERSONal]]'' (Muse, 1980)\n*''[[Naturally (Houston Person album)|Naturally]]'' (HighNote, 2012)\n'''With [[Dave Pike]]'''\n*''[[Pike's Groove]]'' (Criss Cross Jazz, 1986)\n'''With [[Sonny Red]]'''\n*''[[The Mode]]'' (Jazzland, 1961)\n*''[[Sonny Red (album)|Sonny Red]]'' (Mainstream, 1971)\n\n'''With [[Woody Shaw]]'''\n*''[[Setting Standards]]'' (Muse, 1983)\n\n'''With [[Archie Shepp]]'''\n*''[[For Losers]]'' (Impulse!, 1969)\n*''[[Kwanza (album)|Kwanza]]'' (Impulse!, 1969)\n'''With [[James Spaulding]]'''\n*''[[James Spaulding Plays the Legacy of Duke Ellington]]'' (Storyville, 1977)\n'''With [[Idrees Sulieman]]'''\n*''[[Now Is the Time (Idrees Sulieman album)|Now Is the Time]]'' (SteepleChase, 1976)\n\n'''With Jay Thomas'''\n*''Easy Does It'' (Discovery, 1985)\n\n'''With [[Lucky Thompson]]'''\n*''[[Goodbye Yesterday]]'' (Groove Merchant, 1973)\n*''[[Concert: Friday the 13th - Cook County Jail]]'' (Groove Merchant, 1973)\n*''[[I Offer You]]'' (Groove Merchant, 1973)\n\n'''With [[Stanley Turrentine]]'''\n*''[[Another Story (Stanley Turrentine album)|Another Story]]'' (Blue Note, 1969)\n*''[[More Than a Mood]]'' (MusicMasters, 1992)\n\n'''With [[David \"Happy\" Williams|David Williams]]'''\n*''[[Up Front (album)|Up Front]]'' (Timeless, 1987)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|0910486}}\n* [https://ethaniverson.com/interview-with-cedar-walton/ Interview with Cedar Walton], Do The Math, March 2010.\n* Richard Brody, [http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2013/08/cedar-walton-and-the-death-of-jazz.html \"The Glorious Cedar Walton\"], ''The New Yorker'', August 26, 2013.\n\n{{Cedar Walton}}\n{{Jazz Messengers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walton, Cedar}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:American jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:American male pianists]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Blue Note Records artists]]\n[[Category:Chesky Records artists]]\n[[Category:Cobblestone Records artists]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Concord Records artists]]\n[[Category:Contemporary Records artists]]\n[[Category:Criss Cross Jazz artists]]\n[[Category:Discovery Records artists]]\n[[Category:Galaxy Records artists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop pianists]]\n[[Category:HighNote Records artists]]\n[[Category:Impulse! Records artists]]\n[[Category:The Jazz Messengers members]]\n[[Category:Mainstream Records artists]]\n[[Category:Muse Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Odin Records artists]]\n[[Category:Pablo Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Dallas]]\n[[Category:Prestige Records artists]]\n[[Category:Private Music artists]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:RCA Victor artists]]\n[[Category:Red Records artists]]\n[[Category:Riverside Records artists]]\n[[Category:SteepleChase Records artists]]\n[[Category:Strata-East Records artists]]\n[[Category:Telarc Records artists]]\n[[Category:Timeless Records artists]]\n[[Category:Transatlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:University of Denver alumni]]\n[[Category:Venus Records artists]]\n[[Category:Verve Records artists]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:The Jazztet members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Cedar Walton\n| image               = Cedar Walton Dachau 2001.JPG\n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Cedar Anthony Walton, Jr.\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = January 17, 1934\n| birth_place         = [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], United States\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2013|8|19|1934|1|17}}\n| death_place         = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| genre               = [[Jazz]], [[Hard bop]]\n| occupation          = Musician\n| instrument          = [[Piano]]\n| years_active        = \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Cedar Anthony Walton, Jr.''' (January 17, 1934 \u2013 August 19, 2013) was an American [[hard bop]] [[jazz]] pianist. He came to prominence as a member of drummer [[Art Blakey]]'s band before establishing a long career as a bandleader and composer. Several of his compositions have become [[jazz standards]], including \"Mosaic\", \"Bolivia\", \"Holy Land\", \"Mode for Joe\" and \"Fantasy in D\".<ref>William Yardley, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/21/arts/music/cedar-walton-pianist-and-composer-dies-at-79.html?adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1386798234-m9qDE6bMIcVW++St+uJUkQ \"Cedar Walton, Pianist and Composer, Dies at 79\"], ''The New York Times'', August 20, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWalton was born and grew up in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]].<ref name=DownBeat>[http://www.downbeat.com/default.asp?sect=news&subsect=news_detail&nid=2200 \"Pianist-Composer Cedar Walton Dies at Age 79\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215040204/http://www.downbeat.com/default.asp?sect=news&subsect=news_detail&nid=2200 |date=2013-12-15 }}, ''DownBeat'', August 20, 2013.</ref> His mother Ruth was an aspiring concert pianist, and was Walton's initial teacher.<ref>[[John Fordham (jazz critic)|John Fordham]], [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/aug/23/cedar-walton \"Cedar Walton obituary\"], ''Guardian'', August 23, 2013.</ref> She also took him to jazz performances around Dallas. Walton cited [[Nat King Cole]], [[Bud Powell]], [[Thelonious Monk]] and [[Art Tatum]] as his major influences on piano.<ref>Deardra Shuler, [http://www.amsterdamnews.com/arts_and_entertainment/cedar-walton-and-barry-harris-to-play-jazz-at-lincoln/article_4f906fe0-d9c1-11e2-b316-0019bb2963f4.html \"Cedar Walton and Barry Harris to play Jazz at Lincoln Center\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130624204539/http://www.amsterdamnews.com/arts_and_entertainment/cedar-walton-and-barry-harris-to-play-jazz-at-lincoln/article_4f906fe0-d9c1-11e2-b316-0019bb2963f4.html |date=2013-06-24 }}, ''New York Amsterdam News'', June 20, 2013.</ref> He began emulating recordings of these artists from an early age.\n\nAfter briefly attending [[Dillard University]] in [[New Orleans]],<ref name=DownBeat /> he went to the [[University of Denver]] as a composition major originally, but was encouraged to switch to a music education program targeted to set up a career in the local public school system. This switch later proved extremely useful since Walton learned to play and arrange for various instruments, a talent he would hone with [[Art Blakey|Art Blakey's Jazz Messengers]].\n\nWalton was tempted by the promise of New York City through his associations with [[John Coltrane]], [[Charlie Parker]], and [[Richie Powell]], whom he met at various after-hours sessions around the city of [[Denver]], [[Colorado]]. In 1955, he decided to leave school and drove with a friend to New York City. He quickly got recognition from Johnny Garry, who ran [[Birdland (jazz club)|Birdland]] at that time.\n\n==Later life and career==\nWalton was drafted into the U.S. Army, and stationed in Germany, cutting short his rising status in the after-hours scene. While in the Army, he played with musicians [[Leo Wright]], [[Don Ellis]], and [[Eddie Harris]]. Upon his discharge after two years, Walton picked up where he left off, playing as a sideman with [[Kenny Dorham]] (on whose 1958 album ''[[This Is the Moment!]]'' Walton made his recording debut),<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/music-obituaries/10255554/Cedar-Walton.html \"Cedar Walton\" (obituary)], ''The Telegraph'', August 20, 2013.</ref> [[J. J. Johnson]], and with [[Gigi Gryce]].<ref name=Lastfm>[http://www.last.fm/music/Cedar+Walton Cedar Walton page at Last.fm.]</ref> Joining [[the Jazztet]], led by [[Benny Golson]] and [[Art Farmer]], Walton played with this group from 1958 to 1961. In April 1959, he recorded an alternate take of \"[[Giant Steps (composition)|Giant Steps]]\" with John Coltrane, though he did not solo.\n\nIn the early 1960s, Walton joined Art Blakey's Jazz Messengers as a pianist-[[Arrangement|arranger]] for three years, on the same day as [[Freddie Hubbard]]. In this group, which also featured [[Wayne Shorter]], he demonstrated a keen sense of arranging in originals such as \"Ugetsu\" and \"Mosaic\". He left the Messengers in 1964 and by the late 1960s was part of the house [[rhythm section]] at [[Prestige Records]], where in addition to releasing his own recordings, he recorded with [[Sonny Criss]], [[Pat Martino]], [[Eric Kloss]], and [[Charles McPherson (musician)|Charles McPherson]]. For a year, he served as [[Abbey Lincoln]]'s accompanist, and recorded with [[Lee Morgan]] from 1966 to 1968. During the mid-1970s, he led the [[funk]] group Mobius.<ref name=Lastfm /> Walton arranged and recorded for [[Etta James]] from the mid 1990s helping her to win a [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Vocal Album]] for ''[[Mystery Lady: Songs of Billie Holiday]]'' (RCA Victor) in 1994.<ref>Appelbaum, L., [https://larryappelbaum.wordpress.com/2011/02/21/before-after-cedar-walton/ Before and After: Cedar Walton], JazzTimes, November 5, 2004</ref>\n\nMany of Walton's compositions have been adopted as jazz standards, including \"Firm Roots\", \"Bolivia\", \"Holy Land\", \"Mode for Joe\" and \"Cedar's Blues\". \"Bolivia\" is perhaps his best-known composition, while one of his oldest is \"Fantasy in D\", recorded under the title \"Ugetsu\" by Art Blakey in 1963,<ref>Bailey, Phil (1985), ''Volume 35 - Cedar Walton'', Jamey Aebersold, 1985.</ref> and as \"Polar AC\" by Freddie Hubbard, first in 1971.\n\nIn January 2010, Walton was inducted as a member of the [[NEA Jazz Masters|National Endowment for the Arts Jazz Masters]].<ref>[http://www.nea.gov/honors/jazz/jmCMS/master.php?id=2010_08&type=bio Lifetime Honors, National Endowment for the Arts Jazz Masters.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921122628/http://www.nea.gov/honors/jazz/jmCMS/master.php?id=2010_08&type=bio |date=2013-09-21 }}</ref>\n\nAfter a brief illness, Walton died on August 19, 2013, at his home in [[Brooklyn, New York]], at the age of 79.<ref>Mark Memmott, [https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2013/08/19/213459582/jazz-pianist-cedar-walton-dies \"Jazz Pianist Cedar Walton Dies\"], NPR, August 19, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===As leader/co-leader===\n*1967: ''[[Cedar!]]'' ([[Prestige Records|Prestige]])\n*1968: ''[[Spectrum (Cedar Walton album)|Spectrum]]'' (Prestige)\n*1969: ''[[The Electric Boogaloo Song]]'' (Prestige)\n*1969: ''[[Soul Cycle]]'' (Prestige)\n*1972: ''[[Breakthrough! (album)|Breakthrough!]]'' ([[Cobblestone Records|Cobblestone]]) with [[Hank Mobley]]\n*1973: ''[[A Night at Boomers, Vol. 1]]'' ([[Muse Records|Muse]])\n*1973: ''[[A Night at Boomers, Vol. 2]]'' (Muse)\n*1974: ''[[Firm Roots (Cedar Walton album)|Firm Roots]]'' (Muse)\n*1974: ''[[Pit Inn (album)|Pit Inn]]'' ([[East Wind Records|East Wind]])\n*1975: ''[[Mobius (album)|Mobius]]'' ([[RCA Records|RCA]])\n*1976: ''[[The Pentagon (album)|The Pentagon]]'' (East Wind)\n*1976: ''[[Beyond Mobius]]'' (RCA)\n*1977: ''[[First Set]]'' ([[SteepleChase Records|SteepleChase]])\n*1977: ''[[Second Set]]'' (SteepleChase)\n*1977: ''[[Third Set]]'' (SteepleChase)\n*1978: ''[[Animation (Cedar Walton album)|Animation]]'' ([[Columbia Records|Columbia]])\n*1979: ''Charmed Circle'' (HighNote)\n*1980: ''[[Soundscapes (album)|Soundscapes]]'' (Columbia)\n*1980: ''[[The Maestro (Cedar Walton album)|The Maestro]]'' (Muse) with [[Abbey Lincoln]]\n*1981: ''[[Piano Solos (Cedar Walton album)|Piano Solos]]'' (Clean Cuts)\n*1981: ''[[Heart & Soul (Ron Carter and Cedar Walton album)|Heart & Soul]]'' (Timeless) with [[Ron Carter]]\n*1982: ''[[Among Friends (Cedar Walton album)|Among Friends]]'' ([[Theresa Records|Theresa]]) \n*1983: ''[[The All American Trio]]'' ([[Baystate]]) with [[Ron Carter]] and [[Jack DeJohnette]]\n*1985: ''[[Cedar's Blues]]'' ([[Red Records|Red]])\n*1985: ''[[The Trio 1]]'' (Red)\n*1985: ''[[The Trio 2]]'' (Red)\n*1985: ''[[The Trio 3]]'' (Red)\n*1985: ''[[Cedar Walton (album)|Cedar Walton]]'' (Timeless)\n*1985: ''[[Bluesville Time]]'' ([[Criss Cross Jazz|Criss Cross]])\n*1986: ''[[Blues for Myself]]'' (Red)\n*1986: ''[[Cedar Walton Plays]]'' ([[Delos Records|Delos]])\n*1988: ''Standards'' with the VIP Trio (California Breeze)\n*1988: ''Standards Vol 2'' with the VIP Trio (California Breeze)\n*1990: ''[[Duo (Cedar Walton and David Williams album)|Duo]]'' (Red) with [[David \"Happy\" Williams|David Williams]] [also released as ''Off Minor'']\n*1990: ''[[As Long as There's Music (Cedar Walton album)|As Long as There's Music]]'' (Muse [1993])\n*1992: ''[[Cedar Walton at Maybeck]]'' ([[Concord Jazz]])\n*1992: ''[[Manhattan Afternoon]]'' (Criss Cross)\n*1996: ''[[Composer (album)|Composer]]'' ([[Astor Place (label)|Astor Place]])\n*1997: ''[[Roots (Cedar Walton album)|Roots]]'' (Astor Place)\n*2001: ''[[The Promise Land]]'' ([[HighNote Records|HighNote]])\n*2002: ''[[Latin Tinge]]'' (HighNote)\n*2005: ''[[Underground Memoirs]]'' (HighNote)\n*2005: ''[[Midnight Waltz]]'' ([[Venus Records|Venus]])\n*2006: ''[[One Flight Down]]'' (HighNote)\n*2008: ''[[Seasoned Wood]]'' (HighNote)\n*2009: ''[[Voices Deep Within]]'' (HighNote)\n*2010: ''Cedar Chest'' (HighNote)\n*2011: ''[[The Bouncer (album)|The Bouncer]]'' (HighNote)\n'''With Eastern Rebellion'''\n*1975: ''[[Eastern Rebellion]]'' ([[Timeless Records|Timeless]]) with [[George Coleman]], [[Sam Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]] & [[Billy Higgins]]\n*1977: ''[[Eastern Rebellion 2]]'' (Timeless) with [[Bob Berg]], Sam Jones & Billy Higgins\n*1979: ''[[Eastern Rebellion 3]]'' (Timeless) with [[Curtis Fuller]], Bob Berg, Sam Jones & Billy Higgins\n*1983: ''[[Eastern Rebellion 4]]'' (Timeless) with Curtis Fuller, Bob Berg, [[Alfredo \"Chocolate\" Armenteros]], [[David \"Happy\" Williams|David Williams]] & Billy Higgins\n*1990: ''[[Mosaic (Eastern Rebellion album)|Mosaic]]'' ([[MusicMasters Records|MusicMasters]]) with [[Ralph Moore]], David Williams & Billy Higgins\n*1992: ''[[Simple Pleasure (Eastern Rebellion album)|Simple Pleasure]]'' (MusicMasters) with Ralph Moore, David Williams & Billy Higgins\n*1994: ''Just One of Those... Nights at the Village Vanguard'' (MusicMasters) with Ralph Moore, David Williams & Billy Higgins\n\n'''With the Timeless All Stars'''\n*1982: ''[[It's Timeless]]'' (Timeless)\n*1983: ''[[Timeless Heart]]'' (Timeless)\n*1986: ''Essence'' (Delos)\n*1991: ''Time for the Timeless All Stars'' ([[Early Bird Records|Early Bird]])\n\n===As sideman===\n'''With [[Gene Ammons]] and [[Sonny Stitt]]'''\n*''[[God Bless Jug and Sonny]]'' (Prestige, 1973 [2001])\n*''[[Left Bank Encores]]'' (Prestige, 1973 [2001])\n\n'''With [[Art Blakey]]'''\n*''[[Mosaic (Art Blakey album)|Mosaic]]'' (Blue Note, 1961)\n*''[[Three Blind Mice (album)|Three Blind Mice]]'' (Blue Note, 1962)\n*''[[Caravan (Art Blakey album)|Caravan]]'' (Riverside, 1963)\n*''[[Ugetsu (album)|Ugetsu]]'' (Riverside, 1963)\n*''[[Buhaina's Delight]]'' (Blue Note, 1963)\n*''[[Free for All (album)|Free for All]]'' (Blue Note, 1964)\n*''[[Kyoto (Art Blakey album)|Kyoto]]'' (Riverside, 1964)\n*''[[Indestructible (Art Blakey album)|Indestructible]]'' (Blue Note, 1964)\n*''[[Golden Boy (Art Blakey album)|Golden Boy]]'' ([[Colpix Records|Colpix]], 1964)\n*''[[Buhaina]]'' (Prestige, 1973)\n*''[[Anthenagin]]'' (Prestige, 1973)\n\n'''With [[Ray Brown (musician)|Ray Brow